textBeforeTable: The action starts this Thursday, and the most interesting groups for Round 1 include: Chris Trotman/Getty Images Pairings Next » 8 of 6 « Prev Sun Young Yoo has posted seven top-10 finishes in 12 appearances and sits fifth in the Player of the Year race. This year, you should keep an eye on China's Shanshan Feng, who became a first-time winner in the tour's second major, the Wegmans LPGA Championship. In 2009, Eun-Hee Ji shot par in the final round to surpass Cristie Kerr, who shot four-over par. Two years later, Hee Kyung Seo and So Yeon Ryu went into a playoff, the first one since 2006, when Annika Sorenstam defeated Pat Hurst. In the last few years, the U.S. Women's Open has characterized by unexpected winners, especially from Asia. The clearest case is Birdie Kim, who sank her bunker shot for birdie on the 72nd hole, enough to claim the trophy. Streeter Lecka/Getty Images
textAfterTable: You can find the complete list here. « Prev 7 of 8 Next » TV and Online Schedule David Cannon/Getty Images The NBC and ESPN will air the U.S. Women's Open as follows: Day Network Time EDT Thursday, July 5 ESPN 2 4:00 to8:00 p.m. Friday, July 6 ESPN 2 4:00-8:00 p.m. Saturday, July 7 NBC 3:00-6:00 p.m. Sunday, July 8 NBC 3:00-6:00 p.m. If you want to catch the event online, you must tune ESPN3, which will livestream the first two rounds, also from 4:00 to 8:00 p.m. EDT.
